---
description: Python coding conventions for this workspace
globs: **/*.py
alwaysApply: false
---

1. Follow PEP 8 guidelines as a default. The following rules take precedence.
2. Don't use import statements inside functions, unless it actually needs to be there. Put imports at the top of the file. Use separate sections for stdlib modules, third-party modules and local modules. Sort each section alphabetically.
3. Use `pathlib` for all path related operations, whenever possible.
4. Use f-strings for string formatting whenever possible.
5. Use type hints whenever possible.
6. Function arguments and return value should use a single type when possible. Try not to mix types.
7. Code files (i.e. `.py` files) should document the abstractions being used, focusing on the "why". Readers of the code should be able to read docstrings or comments to get a high-level overview of why the code is organized the way it is.
8. For scripts, arguments that users can *reasonably expect to modify* should be exposed using argparse, with suitable defaults. Don't use module level vars for specifying defaults in such cases.
9. Use the logging module whenever possible instead of print.
